{"title_page": "Alternative Democratic Reform Party", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| country = Luxembourg\n| name = Alternative Democratic Reform Party\n| native_name = Alternativ Demokratesch Reformpartei\n| logo = [[File:ADR.png|200px]]\n| leader = [[Jean Schoos]]\n| foundation = 12 May 1987\n| colorcode = #00ADDC\n| split = [[Christian Social People's Party]]<ref name=\"SZ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/luxembourg.html|title=Luxembourg|website=[[Saarbr\u00fccker Zeitung]]|first=Julien|last=Warnand|date=9 October 2018|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n| ideology = [[Conservatism]]<br />[[Right-wing populism]]<br />[[National conservatism]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/luxembourg.html|title=Luxembourg|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|first=Wolfram|last=Nordsieck|year=2018|accessdate=10 April 2019}}</ref><br />[[Economic liberalism]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/><br />[[Soft Euroscepticism]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dumont |first1=Patrick |last2=Fehlen |first2=Fernand |last3=Kies |first3=Rapha\u00ebl |last4=Poirier |first4=Philippe |year=2006 |title=Les \u00e9lections l\u00e9gislatives et europ\u00e9ennes de 2004 au Grand-Duch\u00e9 de Luxembourg |publisher=[[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]] |page=220 |url=http://www.chd.lu/wps/wcm/connect/57c4e7804e295e05b6adf7010df100bc/Rapport_complet_elections2004.pdf?MOD=AJPERES |language=fr}}</ref>\n| position = [[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]]\n| headquarters = 22, rue de l'eau<br />L-1449 [[Luxembourg (city)|Luxembourg]]\n| youth_wing = [[Adrenalin (Luxembourg)|Adrenalin]]\n| international = ''None''\n| european = [[Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe]]\n| colours = [[Red]], [[white]], and [[blue]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.adr.lu}}\n| seats1_title = [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|4|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| seats2_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|6|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| seats3_title = Local councils\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|6|600|hex=#00ADDC}}\n}}\nThe '''Alternative Democratic Reform Party''' ('''ADR'''; {{lang-lb|Alternativ Demokratesch Reformpartei}}, {{lang-fr|Parti r\u00e9formiste d'alternative d\u00e9mocratique}}, {{lang-de|Alternative Demokratische Reformpartei}}) is a [[national conservatism|national-conservative]] and [[Populism|populist]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zulianello|first=Mattia|date=2019|title=Varieties of Populist Parties and Party Systems in Europe: From State-of-the-Art to the Application of a Novel Classification Scheme to 66 Parties in 33 Countries|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/government-and-opposition/article/varieties-of-populist-parties-and-party-systems-in-europe-from-stateoftheart-to-the-application-of-a-novel-classification-scheme-to-66-parties-in-33-countries/7CB95AE2CA7274D5F4716EC11708ACD8|journal=Government and Opposition|volume=|pages=5|via=}}</ref> [[List of political parties in Luxembourg|political party]] in [[Luxembourg]].<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/>  It has four seats in the sixty-seat [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]], making it the fifth-largest party.\n\nThe party was founded in 1987, as a [[single-issue party]] from demanding equality of [[state pension]] provision between [[civil servant]]s and all other citizens.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hirsch |first=Mario |authorlink=Mario Hirsch |date=December 1995 |title=Luxembourg |journal=[[European Journal of Political Research]] |volume=28 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=415\u2013420 |doi=10.1111/j.1475-6765.1995.tb00507.x}}</ref>  In the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1989|1989 election]], it won four seats, and established itself as a political force.  It peaked at seven seats [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1999|in 1999]], due to mistrust of politicians failing to resolve the pensions gap,<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 71</ref> before falling back to four today.  Its significance on a national level makes it the most successful [[pensioners' party]] in western Europe.<ref name=\"Pensioners' parties in Eastern\" />\n\nPolitical success has required the ADR to develop positions on all matters of public policy, developing an [[anti-establishment]],<ref name=\"Pensioners' parties in Eastern\">{{cite journal |last=Hanley |first=Se\u00e1n |year=2007 |title=Pensioners' parties in Eastern and Western Europe: An Overview and Some Theoretical Propositions |url=http://www.inlogov.bham.ac.uk/seminars/minor_parties/pdfs/Hanley.pdf }}</ref> conservative platform.  It has adopted [[economic liberalism]], filling a gap vacated by the [[Democratic Party (Luxembourg)|Democratic Party]].<ref name=\"Dumont 66\">Dumont et al (2006), p. 67</ref>  It is the largest party in [[Luxembourg]] to take a euro-realist/softly eurosceptic line,<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/00344893.2016.1241821|title = 'Euro-Realism' in the 2014 European Parliament Elections: The European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR) and the Democratic Deficit| journal=Representation| volume=52| pages=1\u201312|year = 2016|last1 = Steven|first1 = Martin|url = https://eprints.lancs.ac.uk/id/eprint/83217/2/Article.pdf}}</ref> and is a member of the anti-[[Federal Europe|federalist]] [[Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe]]. The ADR wishes to implement Swiss-style direct democracy. There has been debate whether the party should be classified as populist, although most experts agree that the ADR is better characterised as a national-conservative party.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Niedermayer|first1=Oskar|last2=St\u00f6ss|first2=Richard|last3=Haas|first3=Melanie|title=Die Parteiensysteme Westeuropas|date=2006|publisher=VS Verlag f\u00fcr Sozialwissenschaften|location=Wiesbaden|isbn=978-3531141114|page=329}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=van Kessel|first1=Stijn Theodoor|title=Supply and demand: identifying populist parties in Europe and explaining their electoral performance. Doctoral thesis (DPhil)|date=2001|publisher=University of Sussex|pages=67\u201368|url=http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/7521/1/Van_Kessel%2C_Stijn_Theodoor.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite interview |last=Camus |first=Jean-Yves |subject-link= |interviewer=Christoph Bumb & Pol Schock |title= Extremism-researcher Camus: \"The ADR is not right-wing populist |url=https://www.wort.lu/de/politik/extremismusforscher-jean-yves-camus-die-adr-ist-nicht-rechtspopulistisch-588e44c7a5e74263e13a9c53 |publisher= |location= |date= |work= |access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Federspiel |first1=Sophie |date= October 2016 |title=Rechts abbiegen oder stehen bleiben? Die politische Orientierung der ADR |url=https://www.forum.lu/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/366_Federspiel-1.pdf |journal=Forum|volume= |issue=366 |pages= |doi= |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Emergence===\n{{Politics of Luxembourg}}\nThe ADR has its roots in a demonstration in [[Luxembourg City]] on 28 March 1987, held to protest at the disparities between the 5/6ths [[final salary]] scheme enjoyed by civil servants and the basic state pension received by everyone else.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hirsch |first=Mario |authorlink=Mario Hirsch |date=December 1996 |title=Luxembourg |journal=[[European Journal of Political Research]] |volume=30 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=405\u2013409 |doi=10.1111/j.1475-6765.1996.tb00694.x}}</ref> The large crowd, and the collection of 10,000 signatures for a petition demanding change, persuaded the organisers that there was widespread public support. The party was founded on 12 May 1987 as the 'Action Committee 5/6ths Pensions for Everyone' (''Aktiounskomitee 5/6 Pensioun fir jiddfereen'').<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adr.lu/index.php?id=22 |title=Geschicht vun der Partei |accessdate=2006-08-23 |year=2006 |publisher=Alternative Democratic Reform Party |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722153620/http://www.adr.lu/index.php?id=22 |archivedate=2011-07-22 |language=de |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1989|1989 election]] to the Chamber of Deputies, on 18 June 1989, the party achieved remarkable success by attracting votes from far beyond its core support base. Many Luxembourgers voted for the ADR as a [[protest vote]], allowing the ADR to register 7.3% of the vote, win 4 of the 60 seats, and come fourth.<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> The spectacular triumph of the party in the election required the leadership to formulate a new party strategy. On 12 November 1989, the name was amended to 'Action Committee 5/6ths' (''Aktiounskomitee 5/6''), reflecting its increased attention to other concerns.<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> The party lost one of its deputies, [[Josy Simon]], when he defected to the [[Democratic Party (Luxembourg)|Democratic Party]] in spring 1991.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hirsch |first=Mario |authorlink=Mario Hirsch |date=December 1992 |title=Luxembourg |journal=[[European Journal of Political Research]] |volume=22 |issue=4 |pages=469\u2013470 |doi=10.1111/j.1475-6765.1992.tb00334.x}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 November 1992, the name was changed again, to 'Action Committee for Democracy and Pensions Justice' (''Aktiounskomitee fir Demokratie an Rentengerechtigkeet'').<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> In December of the same year, the prominent deputy [[Fernand Rau]] defected from the [[Christian Social People's Party]] (CSV) after it broke its pledge to make him [[European Commissioner]], increasing the ADR's representation back up to four.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hirsch |first=Mario |authorlink=Mario Hirsch |date=December 1993 |title=Luxembourg |journal=[[European Journal of Political Research]] |volume=24 |issue=4 |pages=491\u2013494 |doi=10.1111/j.1475-6765.1993.tb00402.x}}</ref> At the 10 October 1993 local elections, the ADR won 7 seats in [[Communes of Luxembourg|communal]] councils. At the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1994|1994 general election]], the ADR got 9.0% of the vote and 5 seats, putting the ADR over the threshold required to qualify as a [[caucus]], but the ADR fell to fifth place, behind the resurgent [[The Greens (Luxembourg)|Greens]].<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" />\n\n===Mainstream party===\nOn 3 August 1998, a law was passed equalising pension provision between civil servants and other workers,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/1998/0070/a070.pdf#page=2 | title=M\u00e9morial A, 1998, No. 70 | accessdate=2008-04-20 | format=PDF | publisher=Service central de l\u00e9gislation|language=fr}}</ref> fulfilling the ADR's original ''raison d'\u00eatre'', but this did not prevent the ADR from strengthening its position further. In the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1999|1999 legislative election]], the party enjoyed increased success, winning 9.4% of the vote and 7 seats. The results put the ADR back into fourth place, but the Greens managed to hold on to their seat in the simultaneous [[1999 European Parliament election in Luxembourg|European elections]].<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> October 1999 saw ADR candidates elected in ten communes, with two winning in each of [[Luxembourg City]] and [[Esch-sur-Alzette]].<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> The ADR lost two of its Chamber of Deputies seats at the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 2004|2004 general election]], and its share of the vote fell to under 10%.<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" />\n\nOne of ADR's hallmark positions is its [[euroscepticism]], and it is the only eurosceptic party in the Chamber of Deputies.<ref name=\"Luxembourg ratifies Lisbon treaty\">{{cite news |first=Zo\u00eb |last=Casey |title=Luxembourg ratifies Lisbon treaty |url=http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/2008/05/2602/luxembourg-ratifies-lisbon-treaty/60991.aspx |publisher=[[European Voice]] |date=30 May 2008 |accessdate=June 12, 2009}}</ref> It was the only parliamentary party that actively campaigned against the [[Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe]], which was [[Luxembourgian European Constitution referendum, 2005|put to a referendum]] and narrowly passed with 56.5% of voters in favour.\n\nOn 2 April 2006 the name was changed once more, to its current name of 'Alternative Democratic Reform Party' (''Alternativ Demokratesch Reformpartei'').<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> Significantly, for the first time, the name makes no reference to pension reform, signalling the eagerness of the ADR to further solidify its position as a major party in national politics. However, on 1 May, [[Aly Jaerling]] left the party to sit as an [[Independent (politician)|independent]] in the Chamber of Deputies, complaining of the move away from campaigning for pensions.<ref name=\"Jaerling prend la tangente\">{{cite web|url=http://www.paperjam.lu/c/articles/15245.html |title=ADR: Jaerling prend la tangente |accessdate=2006-08-23 |date=2006-04-21 |publisher=PaperJam.lu|language=fr}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> As a result of Jaerling's departure, the party lost its status as a caucus and now only qualifies as a 'group', threatening its future security.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.investigateur.info/zines/textes/315_3.html |title=Le hara-kiri d'Aly Jaerling |accessdate=2006-08-23 |year=2006 |publisher=L'investigateur |language=fr |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070506143726/http://www.investigateur.info/zines/textes/315_3.html |archivedate=May 6, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2008, the ADR deputies and Jaerling were the only members not to vote for the [[Treaty of Lisbon]]. In the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 2009|2009 Chamber election]], the ADR held on to four seats (of which, 2 in [[Circonscription Sud (Luxembourg)|Sud]]), but with a reduced vote share of 8.1%: its worst legislative election result since its first election, in 1989, whilst its vote share fell - albeit by less - in the simultaneous [[2009 European Parliament election in Luxembourg|European Parliament election]], to 7.4%. Jaerling, running for his own [[Citizens' List]], failed to win a seat in either. This had been in spite of strong pre-election polling, the difference likely to be attributable to the financial crisis pushing voters to more familiar parties.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nOn 8 June 2010, the ADR joined the [[Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe]], a Euro-Realist [[European political party|Europe-wide political party]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ecrgroup.eu/about-us/our-history/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=17 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219204118/http://ecrgroup.eu/about-us/our-history/ |archive-date=19 February 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the snap-election of 2013, the ADR once again fell in their share of the vote, from 8.14% to 6.64%. However, they did manage to regain one seat, having fallen to only two MPs after the defections of [[Jacques-Yves Henckes]] and [[Jean Colombera]]. The former sat out the 2009-2013 legislative period as an independent, the latter founded the [[Party for Full Democracy]]. [[Roy Reding]] regained the mandate in the Centre district, putting the party back at 3 mandates.\n\nDuring the [[Luxembourg constitutional referendum, 2015|Constitutional Referendum Campaign of 2015]], the ADR was the only party to explicitly campaign for the \"3 x No\" vote, thereby rejecting the opening of the right to vote for 16 year-olds and foreign residents, as well as rejecting the idea of limiting minister mandates to 10 years. This campaign was in stark contrast to the campaign of the largest party, the CSV, whose main message was to \"be informed\" when voting. With each question being rejected by between 70% and 80% of the electorate,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.elections.public.lu/content/dam/elections/fr/referendum/2015/resultats-officiels/referendum-resultats-officiels.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=17 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226151213/http://www.elections.public.lu/content/dam/elections/fr/referendum/2015/resultats-officiels/referendum-resultats-officiels.pdf |archive-date=26 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> this event represented a big political win for the ADR in face of the incumbent Government.\n\n3 years after the Referendum, on 2 March 2018, the ADR announced that it would be co-operating with the citizen's movement [[Wee 2050 - Nee 2015]], which had been founded pre-referendum to campaign for the \"3 x No\". The cooperation agreement involved Wee 2050 having up to 8 places on the ADR's electoral lists for the legislative election of October 2018, and ensured that the movement could remain relatively independent by not requiring the Wee 2050 candidates to be members of the ADR per se.\n\n==Ideology==\nThe party was founded as a single-issue party, to introduce equality between private and public sector pensions.  The focus on pension reform allowed it to make it the core campaign issue of all five elections in the first ten years of its formation.<ref>Immergut et al (2007), p. 36</ref>  By 1998, the party had forced the government to accede almost all of its demands.<ref name=\"Immergut 838\">Immergut et al (2007), p. 838</ref>  However, this success has not thwarted the ADR,<ref name=\"Immergut 838\" /> and it has diversified its programme to cover all aspects of public policy.\n\nThe party is a supporter of [[economic liberalism]], having positioned itself to fill a void left by the [[Democratic Party (Luxembourg)|Democratic Party]].<ref name=\"Dumont 66\" />  The party is critical of public sector waste and the 'elitist' nature of public spending projects.<ref name=\"Pensioners' parties in Eastern\" />  The ADR is [[social conservatism|socially conservative]].  It is opposed to [[euthanasia]] and [[assisted suicide]].<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 77</ref>  The party places great importance on promoting the [[Luxembourgish language]], and its electoral success in the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1999|1999 election]] pushed the CSV-DP government to make knowledge of it a criterion for [[naturalization|naturalisation]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Acquisition and Loss of Nationality: Policies and Trends in 15 European States \u2013 Volume 2: Country Analysis |editor1-first=Rainer |editor1-last=Baub\u00f6ck |editor2-first=Eva |editor2-last=Ersb\u00f8ll |editor3-first=Kees |editor3-last=Groenendijk |editor4-first=Harald |editor4-last=Waldrauch |first=Fran\u00e7ois |last=Moyse |author2=Brasseur, Pierre|author3= Scuto, Denis |year=2004 |publisher=Amsterdam University Press |location=Amsterdam |chapter=Luxembourg |isbn=978-90-5356-921-4 |page=380 }}</ref>  It is opposed to [[multiple citizenship]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Acquisition and Loss of Nationality: Policies and Trends in 15 European States |last=Baub\u00f6ck |first=Rainer |author2=Ersboll, Eva |year=2006 |publisher=Amsterdam University Press |location=Amsterdam |page=237 |isbn=978-90-5356-920-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nFmjkTnXNQAC }}</ref>\n\nThe party is marked out from the other parties by being [[Eurosceptic]],<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 220</ref> sharing this position with only the [[far left]],<ref name=\"Dumont 95\">Dumont et al (2006), p. 95</ref> and being the country's most [[Souverainism|sovereigntist]] party.<ref name=\"Maier 144\">Maier et al (2004), p. 144</ref>  The leadership had supported the proposed [[European Constitution]], endorsing it in the [[2004 European Parliament election in Luxembourg|2004 European election]],<ref name=\"Maier 144\" /> before changing its position in the spring of 2005 under pressure from party members.<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 92</ref>  In its criticism of the [[European Union|EU]], the party puts emphasis on the [[democratic deficit]] and [[Transparency (behavior)|transparency]].<ref name=\"Dumont 95\" />  However, in heavily [[pro-Europeanism|pro-European]] Luxembourg, the ADR had always fared worse in European elections than on national elections, which were held on the same day.<ref>Maier et al (2004), p. 143</ref> This was the case only until 2014, when the party achieved a slightly better score than it had in the early 2013 national elections, managing to beat the [[LSAP]] in the majority of communes.\n\n==Political support==\nThe ADR's primary political base are the CSV's 'traditional, rural and rightist' voters.<ref>Van Hecke et al (2004), p. 180</ref>  Although the ADR is seen to take votes from the right wing of the CSV,<ref>Van Hecke et al (2004), p. 182</ref> more ADR voters declare themselves to be [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] than either the CSV or DP.<ref>Van Hecke et al (2004), p. 187</ref>  Much of the party's support is in the north of the country,<ref name=\"Dumont 124\">Dumont et al (2006), p. 124</ref> where the ADR received its strongest support in the 1999 (16.7%), 2004 (14.7%) and [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 2009|2009 Chamber elections]] (10.3%). In 2013 however it received its highest share of the vote in the [[Est (Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg constituency)|Est]] constituency.\n\nDue to the party's original purpose of pension equality, the party's electoral base is pensioners.  However, disproportionately many people under the age of 24 also see the ADR in a positive light.<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 127\u20138</ref>  ADR is particularly popular on the [[Internet]], despite the party leadership's lack of interest in the medium, due in part to its popularity amongst young people.<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 156</ref>  The party is most popular amongst people earning less than \u20ac30,000,<ref name=\"Dumont 124\" /> and has attracted support from the part of the CSV's core electorate that have been left out of recent economic growth.<ref>Van Hecke et al (2004), p. 195</ref>  As with the CSV and LSAP, the ADR is supported by people with less education.<ref>Van Hecke et al (2004), p. 185</ref>\n\nThe party is backed by the third-largest general trade union in the country, the small [[Neutral Union of Luxembourg Workers]] (NGL), which has been the driving force behind the ADR.<ref name=\"Immergut 815\">Immergut et al (2007), p. 815</ref>  The ADR has also been close to the [[Luxembourg Association of Retired and Invalid People]] (LRIV), which formerly backed the [[Communist Party of Luxembourg|Communist Party]].<ref name=\"Immergut 815\" />  The party has used local celebrities, such as [[Jean-Pierre Koepp]] in [[Circonscription Nord (Luxembourg)|Nord]], to boost its appeal.<ref>Immergut et al (2007), p. 849</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|-\n! Election\n! Votes\n! %\n! Seats\n! +/\u2013\n! Position\n! Government\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 1989|1989]]\n| 225,262\n| 7.9\n| {{Composition bar|4|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| {{steady}} 0\n| {{steady}} 4th\n| {{no2|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 1994|1994]]\n| 244,045\n| 9.0\n| {{Composition bar|5|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n| {{decrease}} 5th\n| {{no2|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 1999|1999]]\n| 303,734\n| 11.3\n| {{Composition bar|7|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| {{increase}} 2\n| {{increase}} 4th\n| {{no2|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 2004|2004]]\n| 278,792\n| 10.0\n| {{Composition bar|5|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| {{decrease}} 2\n| {{decrease}} 5th\n| {{no2|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 2009|2009]]\n| 303,734\n| 11.3\n| {{Composition bar|4|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| {{decrease}} 1\n| {{steady}} 5th\n| {{no2|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 2013|2013]]\n| 217,683\n| 6.6\n| {{Composition bar|3|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| {{decrease}} 1\n| {{steady}} 5th\n| {{no2|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 2018|2018]]\n| 292,388\n| 8.3\n| {{Composition bar|4|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n| {{steady}} 5th\n| {{no2|Opposition}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Leaders==\n\n===Party presidents===\n* [[Gaston Gib\u00e9ryen]] (1987\u20131989)\n* [[John Bram]] (1989\u20131991)\n* [[Robert Mehlen]] (1991 \u2013 2013)\n* [[Fernand Kartheiser]] (2013)\n* [[Jean Schoos]] (2013 \u2013 present)\n\n==Elected representatives==\nSince its formation, the ADR has had eleven [[deputy (legislator)|deputies]] in the [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]].  Its four current deputies are given in '''bold'''.\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n* [[Jean Colombera]] ([[Circonscription Nord (Luxembourg)|Nord]]: 1999\u20132004, 2009\u20132013)\n* '''[[Gaston Gib\u00e9ryen]]''' ([[Circonscription Sud (Luxembourg)|Sud]]: 1989\u2013present)\n* [[Fernand Greisen]]  ([[Circonscription Centre (Luxembourg)|Centre]]: 1999\u20132004)\n* [[Jacques-Yves Henckes]] ([[Circonscription Centre (Luxembourg)|Centre]]: 1994\u20132013)\n* [[Aly Jaerling]] ([[Circonscription Sud (Luxembourg)|Sud]]: 1999\u20132006)\n{{Col-2}}\n* '''[[Fernand Kartheiser]]''' ([[Circonscription Sud (Luxembourg)|Sud]]: 2009\u2013present)\n* [[Jean-Pierre Koepp]] ([[Circonscription Nord (Luxembourg)|Nord]]: 1989\u20132009)\n* [[Robert Mehlen]] ([[Circonscription Est (Luxembourg)|Est]]: 1989\u20132009)\n* [[Fernand Rau]] ([[Circonscription Centre (Luxembourg)|Centre]]: 1992\u201394)\n* [[Josy Simon]] ([[Circonscription Centre (Luxembourg)|Centre]]: 1989\u201391)\n* '''[[Roy Reding]]''' ([[Circonscription Centre (Luxembourg)|Centre]]: 2013\u2013present)\n* '''[[Jeff Engelen]]''' ([[Circonscription Nord (Luxembourg)|Nord]]: 2018-)\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|conservatism}}\n* [[List of political parties in Luxembourg]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite interview |last=Camus |first=Jean-Yves |subject-link= |interviewer=Christoph Bumb & Pol Schock |title= Extremism-researcher Camus: \"The ADR is not right-wing populist |url=https://www.wort.lu/de/politik/extremismusforscher-jean-yves-camus-die-adr-ist-nicht-rechtspopulistisch-588e44c7a5e74263e13a9c53 |publisher= |location= |date= |work= |access-date=}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Dumont |first1=Patrick |last2=Fehlen |first2=Fernand |last3=Kies |first3=Rapha\u00ebl |last4=Poirier |first4=Philippe |year=2006 |title=Les \u00e9lections l\u00e9gislatives et europ\u00e9ennes de 2004 au Grand-Duch\u00e9 de Luxembourg |publisher=[[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]] |url=http://www.chd.lu/wps/wcm/connect/57c4e7804e295e05b6adf7010df100bc/Rapport_complet_elections2004.pdf?MOD=AJPERES |language=fr}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Handbook of West European Pension Politics |last=Immergut |first=Ellen M. |author2=Anderson, Karen M.|author3= Schulze, Isabelle |year=2007 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-929147-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T0pYjE6REq4C }}\n* {{cite book |title=Campaigning in Europe - Campaigning for Europe |last=Maier |first=Michaela |author2=Tenscher, Jens |year=2004 |publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster |location=M\u00fcnster |isbn=978-3-8258-9322-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j9NjsybIcgoC }}\n* {{cite book |title=Christian Democratic Parties in Europe Since the End of the Cold War |last=Van Hecke |first=Steven |author2=Gerard, Emmanuel |year=2004 |publisher=Leuven University Press |location=Leuven |isbn=978-90-5867-377-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QJ6x8zmRAaEC }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|lb}} [http://www.adr.lu/ Alternative Democratic Reform Party official website]\n\n{{Luxembourgian political parties}}\n{{Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Conservative parties in Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Pensioners' parties]]\n[[Category:Eurosceptic parties in Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe member parties]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1987]]\n[[Category:1987 establishments in Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:National conservative parties]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populist parties]]\n[[Category:Luxembourgian nationalism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| country = Luxembourg\n| name = Alternative Democratic Reform Party\n| native_name = Alternativ Demokratesch Reformpartei\n| logo = [[File:ADR.png|200px]]\n| leader = [[Jean Schoos]]\n| foundation = 12 May 1987\n| colorcode = #00ADDC\n| split = [[Christian Social People's Party]]<ref name=\"SZ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/luxembourg.html|title=Luxembourg|website=[[Saarbr\u00fccker Zeitung]]|first=Julien|last=Warnand|date=9 October 2018|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n| ideology = [[Conservatism]]<br />[[Right-wing populism]]<br />[[National conservatism]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/luxembourg.html|title=Luxembourg|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|first=Wolfram|last=Nordsieck|year=2018|accessdate=10 April 2019}}</ref><br />[[Economic liberalism]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/><br />[[Soft Euroscepticism]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dumont |first1=Patrick |last2=Fehlen |first2=Fernand |last3=Kies |first3=Rapha\u00ebl |last4=Poirier |first4=Philippe |year=2006 |title=Les \u00e9lections l\u00e9gislatives et europ\u00e9ennes de 2004 au Grand-Duch\u00e9 de Luxembourg |publisher=[[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]] |page=220 |url=http://www.chd.lu/wps/wcm/connect/57c4e7804e295e05b6adf7010df100bc/Rapport_complet_elections2004.pdf?MOD=AJPERES |language=fr}}</ref>\n| position = [[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://luxtimes.lu/luxembourg/39268-adr-vice-president-resigns-over-facebook-comments|title=ADR vice-president resigns over Facebook comments|quote=The vice-president of Luxembourg's right-wing party ADR has resigned over comments she made on the foreign ministers' Facebook post on taking refugees from Niger.|work=Luxembourg Times|date=10 December 2019}}</ref> to [[Far-right politics|far-right]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://delano.lu/d/detail/news/10-things-we-learned-2018-election/193000|title=10 things we learned from the 2018 election|quote=The far right ADR managed to make a gain of just 1.64% of the popular vote across the country.|work=Delano.lu|date=15 October 2018}}</ref>\n| headquarters = 22, rue de l'eau<br />L-1449 [[Luxembourg (city)|Luxembourg]]\n| youth_wing = [[Adrenalin (Luxembourg)|Adrenalin]]\n| international = ''None''\n| european = [[Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe]]\n| colours = [[Red]], [[white]], and [[blue]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.adr.lu}}\n| seats1_title = [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|4|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| seats2_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|6|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| seats3_title = Local councils\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|6|600|hex=#00ADDC}}\n}}\nThe '''Alternative Democratic Reform Party''' ('''ADR'''; {{lang-lb|Alternativ Demokratesch Reformpartei}}, {{lang-fr|Parti r\u00e9formiste d'alternative d\u00e9mocratique}}, {{lang-de|Alternative Demokratische Reformpartei}}) is a [[national conservatism|national-conservative]] and [[Populism|populist]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zulianello|first=Mattia|date=2019|title=Varieties of Populist Parties and Party Systems in Europe: From State-of-the-Art to the Application of a Novel Classification Scheme to 66 Parties in 33 Countries|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/government-and-opposition/article/varieties-of-populist-parties-and-party-systems-in-europe-from-stateoftheart-to-the-application-of-a-novel-classification-scheme-to-66-parties-in-33-countries/7CB95AE2CA7274D5F4716EC11708ACD8|journal=Government and Opposition|volume=|pages=5|via=}}</ref> [[List of political parties in Luxembourg|political party]] in [[Luxembourg]].<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/>  It has four seats in the sixty-seat [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]], making it the fifth-largest party.\n\nThe party was founded in 1987, as a [[single-issue party]] from demanding equality of [[state pension]] provision between [[civil servant]]s and all other citizens.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hirsch |first=Mario |authorlink=Mario Hirsch |date=December 1995 |title=Luxembourg |journal=[[European Journal of Political Research]] |volume=28 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=415\u2013420 |doi=10.1111/j.1475-6765.1995.tb00507.x}}</ref>  In the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1989|1989 election]], it won four seats, and established itself as a political force.  It peaked at seven seats [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1999|in 1999]], due to mistrust of politicians failing to resolve the pensions gap,<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 71</ref> before falling back to four today.  Its significance on a national level makes it the most successful [[pensioners' party]] in western Europe.<ref name=\"Pensioners' parties in Eastern\" />\n\nPolitical success has required the ADR to develop positions on all matters of public policy, developing an [[anti-establishment]],<ref name=\"Pensioners' parties in Eastern\">{{cite journal |last=Hanley |first=Se\u00e1n |year=2007 |title=Pensioners' parties in Eastern and Western Europe: An Overview and Some Theoretical Propositions |url=http://www.inlogov.bham.ac.uk/seminars/minor_parties/pdfs/Hanley.pdf }}</ref> conservative platform.  It has adopted [[economic liberalism]], filling a gap vacated by the [[Democratic Party (Luxembourg)|Democratic Party]].<ref name=\"Dumont 66\">Dumont et al (2006), p. 67</ref>  It is the largest party in [[Luxembourg]] to take a euro-realist/softly eurosceptic line,<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1080/00344893.2016.1241821|title = 'Euro-Realism' in the 2014 European Parliament Elections: The European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR) and the Democratic Deficit| journal=Representation| volume=52| pages=1\u201312|year = 2016|last1 = Steven|first1 = Martin|url = https://eprints.lancs.ac.uk/id/eprint/83217/2/Article.pdf}}</ref> and is a member of the anti-[[Federal Europe|federalist]] [[Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe]]. The ADR wishes to implement Swiss-style direct democracy. There has been debate whether the party should be classified as populist, although most experts agree that the ADR is better characterised as a national-conservative party.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Niedermayer|first1=Oskar|last2=St\u00f6ss|first2=Richard|last3=Haas|first3=Melanie|title=Die Parteiensysteme Westeuropas|date=2006|publisher=VS Verlag f\u00fcr Sozialwissenschaften|location=Wiesbaden|isbn=978-3531141114|page=329}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=van Kessel|first1=Stijn Theodoor|title=Supply and demand: identifying populist parties in Europe and explaining their electoral performance. Doctoral thesis (DPhil)|date=2001|publisher=University of Sussex|pages=67\u201368|url=http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/7521/1/Van_Kessel%2C_Stijn_Theodoor.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite interview |last=Camus |first=Jean-Yves |subject-link= |interviewer=Christoph Bumb & Pol Schock |title= Extremism-researcher Camus: \"The ADR is not right-wing populist |url=https://www.wort.lu/de/politik/extremismusforscher-jean-yves-camus-die-adr-ist-nicht-rechtspopulistisch-588e44c7a5e74263e13a9c53 |publisher= |location= |date= |work= |access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Federspiel |first1=Sophie |date= October 2016 |title=Rechts abbiegen oder stehen bleiben? Die politische Orientierung der ADR |url=https://www.forum.lu/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/366_Federspiel-1.pdf |journal=Forum|volume= |issue=366 |pages= |doi= |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Emergence===\n{{Politics of Luxembourg}}\nThe ADR has its roots in a demonstration in [[Luxembourg City]] on 28 March 1987, held to protest at the disparities between the 5/6ths [[final salary]] scheme enjoyed by civil servants and the basic state pension received by everyone else.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hirsch |first=Mario |authorlink=Mario Hirsch |date=December 1996 |title=Luxembourg |journal=[[European Journal of Political Research]] |volume=30 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=405\u2013409 |doi=10.1111/j.1475-6765.1996.tb00694.x}}</ref> The large crowd, and the collection of 10,000 signatures for a petition demanding change, persuaded the organisers that there was widespread public support. The party was founded on 12 May 1987 as the 'Action Committee 5/6ths Pensions for Everyone' (''Aktiounskomitee 5/6 Pensioun fir jiddfereen'').<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adr.lu/index.php?id=22 |title=Geschicht vun der Partei |accessdate=2006-08-23 |year=2006 |publisher=Alternative Democratic Reform Party |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722153620/http://www.adr.lu/index.php?id=22 |archivedate=2011-07-22 |language=de |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1989|1989 election]] to the Chamber of Deputies, on 18 June 1989, the party achieved remarkable success by attracting votes from far beyond its core support base. Many Luxembourgers voted for the ADR as a [[protest vote]], allowing the ADR to register 7.3% of the vote, win 4 of the 60 seats, and come fourth.<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> The spectacular triumph of the party in the election required the leadership to formulate a new party strategy. On 12 November 1989, the name was amended to 'Action Committee 5/6ths' (''Aktiounskomitee 5/6''), reflecting its increased attention to other concerns.<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> The party lost one of its deputies, [[Josy Simon]], when he defected to the [[Democratic Party (Luxembourg)|Democratic Party]] in spring 1991.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hirsch |first=Mario |authorlink=Mario Hirsch |date=December 1992 |title=Luxembourg |journal=[[European Journal of Political Research]] |volume=22 |issue=4 |pages=469\u2013470 |doi=10.1111/j.1475-6765.1992.tb00334.x}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 November 1992, the name was changed again, to 'Action Committee for Democracy and Pensions Justice' (''Aktiounskomitee fir Demokratie an Rentengerechtigkeet'').<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> In December of the same year, the prominent deputy [[Fernand Rau]] defected from the [[Christian Social People's Party]] (CSV) after it broke its pledge to make him [[European Commissioner]], increasing the ADR's representation back up to four.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hirsch |first=Mario |authorlink=Mario Hirsch |date=December 1993 |title=Luxembourg |journal=[[European Journal of Political Research]] |volume=24 |issue=4 |pages=491\u2013494 |doi=10.1111/j.1475-6765.1993.tb00402.x}}</ref> At the 10 October 1993 local elections, the ADR won 7 seats in [[Communes of Luxembourg|communal]] councils. At the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1994|1994 general election]], the ADR got 9.0% of the vote and 5 seats, putting the ADR over the threshold required to qualify as a [[caucus]], but the ADR fell to fifth place, behind the resurgent [[The Greens (Luxembourg)|Greens]].<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" />\n\n===Mainstream party===\nOn 3 August 1998, a law was passed equalising pension provision between civil servants and other workers,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/1998/0070/a070.pdf#page=2 | title=M\u00e9morial A, 1998, No. 70 | accessdate=2008-04-20 | format=PDF | publisher=Service central de l\u00e9gislation|language=fr}}</ref> fulfilling the ADR's original ''raison d'\u00eatre'', but this did not prevent the ADR from strengthening its position further. In the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1999|1999 legislative election]], the party enjoyed increased success, winning 9.4% of the vote and 7 seats. The results put the ADR back into fourth place, but the Greens managed to hold on to their seat in the simultaneous [[1999 European Parliament election in Luxembourg|European elections]].<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> October 1999 saw ADR candidates elected in ten communes, with two winning in each of [[Luxembourg City]] and [[Esch-sur-Alzette]].<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> The ADR lost two of its Chamber of Deputies seats at the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 2004|2004 general election]], and its share of the vote fell to under 10%.<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" />\n\nOne of ADR's hallmark positions is its [[euroscepticism]], and it is the only eurosceptic party in the Chamber of Deputies.<ref name=\"Luxembourg ratifies Lisbon treaty\">{{cite news |first=Zo\u00eb |last=Casey |title=Luxembourg ratifies Lisbon treaty |url=http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/2008/05/2602/luxembourg-ratifies-lisbon-treaty/60991.aspx |publisher=[[European Voice]] |date=30 May 2008 |accessdate=June 12, 2009}}</ref> It was the only parliamentary party that actively campaigned against the [[Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe]], which was [[Luxembourgian European Constitution referendum, 2005|put to a referendum]] and narrowly passed with 56.5% of voters in favour.\n\nOn 2 April 2006 the name was changed once more, to its current name of 'Alternative Democratic Reform Party' (''Alternativ Demokratesch Reformpartei'').<ref name=\"ADR Geschicht\" /> Significantly, for the first time, the name makes no reference to pension reform, signalling the eagerness of the ADR to further solidify its position as a major party in national politics. However, on 1 May, [[Aly Jaerling]] left the party to sit as an [[Independent (politician)|independent]] in the Chamber of Deputies, complaining of the move away from campaigning for pensions.<ref name=\"Jaerling prend la tangente\">{{cite web|url=http://www.paperjam.lu/c/articles/15245.html |title=ADR: Jaerling prend la tangente |accessdate=2006-08-23 |date=2006-04-21 |publisher=PaperJam.lu|language=fr}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> As a result of Jaerling's departure, the party lost its status as a caucus and now only qualifies as a 'group', threatening its future security.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.investigateur.info/zines/textes/315_3.html |title=Le hara-kiri d'Aly Jaerling |accessdate=2006-08-23 |year=2006 |publisher=L'investigateur |language=fr |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070506143726/http://www.investigateur.info/zines/textes/315_3.html |archivedate=May 6, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2008, the ADR deputies and Jaerling were the only members not to vote for the [[Treaty of Lisbon]]. In the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 2009|2009 Chamber election]], the ADR held on to four seats (of which, 2 in [[Circonscription Sud (Luxembourg)|Sud]]), but with a reduced vote share of 8.1%: its worst legislative election result since its first election, in 1989, whilst its vote share fell - albeit by less - in the simultaneous [[2009 European Parliament election in Luxembourg|European Parliament election]], to 7.4%. Jaerling, running for his own [[Citizens' List]], failed to win a seat in either. This had been in spite of strong pre-election polling, the difference likely to be attributable to the financial crisis pushing voters to more familiar parties.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nOn 8 June 2010, the ADR joined the [[Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe]], a Euro-Realist [[European political party|Europe-wide political party]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ecrgroup.eu/about-us/our-history/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=17 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219204118/http://ecrgroup.eu/about-us/our-history/ |archive-date=19 February 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the snap-election of 2013, the ADR once again fell in their share of the vote, from 8.14% to 6.64%. However, they did manage to regain one seat, having fallen to only two MPs after the defections of [[Jacques-Yves Henckes]] and [[Jean Colombera]]. The former sat out the 2009-2013 legislative period as an independent, the latter founded the [[Party for Full Democracy]]. [[Roy Reding]] regained the mandate in the Centre district, putting the party back at 3 mandates.\n\nDuring the [[Luxembourg constitutional referendum, 2015|Constitutional Referendum Campaign of 2015]], the ADR was the only party to explicitly campaign for the \"3 x No\" vote, thereby rejecting the opening of the right to vote for 16 year-olds and foreign residents, as well as rejecting the idea of limiting minister mandates to 10 years. This campaign was in stark contrast to the campaign of the largest party, the CSV, whose main message was to \"be informed\" when voting. With each question being rejected by between 70% and 80% of the electorate,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.elections.public.lu/content/dam/elections/fr/referendum/2015/resultats-officiels/referendum-resultats-officiels.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=17 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226151213/http://www.elections.public.lu/content/dam/elections/fr/referendum/2015/resultats-officiels/referendum-resultats-officiels.pdf |archive-date=26 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> this event represented a big political win for the ADR in face of the incumbent Government.\n\n3 years after the Referendum, on 2 March 2018, the ADR announced that it would be co-operating with the citizen's movement [[Wee 2050 - Nee 2015]], which had been founded pre-referendum to campaign for the \"3 x No\". The cooperation agreement involved Wee 2050 having up to 8 places on the ADR's electoral lists for the legislative election of October 2018, and ensured that the movement could remain relatively independent by not requiring the Wee 2050 candidates to be members of the ADR per se.\n\n==Ideology==\nThe party was founded as a single-issue party, to introduce equality between private and public sector pensions.  The focus on pension reform allowed it to make it the core campaign issue of all five elections in the first ten years of its formation.<ref>Immergut et al (2007), p. 36</ref>  By 1998, the party had forced the government to accede almost all of its demands.<ref name=\"Immergut 838\">Immergut et al (2007), p. 838</ref>  However, this success has not thwarted the ADR,<ref name=\"Immergut 838\" /> and it has diversified its programme to cover all aspects of public policy.\n\nThe party is a supporter of [[economic liberalism]], having positioned itself to fill a void left by the [[Democratic Party (Luxembourg)|Democratic Party]].<ref name=\"Dumont 66\" />  The party is critical of public sector waste and the 'elitist' nature of public spending projects.<ref name=\"Pensioners' parties in Eastern\" />  The ADR is [[social conservatism|socially conservative]].  It is opposed to [[euthanasia]] and [[assisted suicide]].<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 77</ref>  The party places great importance on promoting the [[Luxembourgish language]], and its electoral success in the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1999|1999 election]] pushed the CSV-DP government to make knowledge of it a criterion for [[naturalization|naturalisation]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Acquisition and Loss of Nationality: Policies and Trends in 15 European States \u2013 Volume 2: Country Analysis |editor1-first=Rainer |editor1-last=Baub\u00f6ck |editor2-first=Eva |editor2-last=Ersb\u00f8ll |editor3-first=Kees |editor3-last=Groenendijk |editor4-first=Harald |editor4-last=Waldrauch |first=Fran\u00e7ois |last=Moyse |author2=Brasseur, Pierre|author3= Scuto, Denis |year=2004 |publisher=Amsterdam University Press |location=Amsterdam |chapter=Luxembourg |isbn=978-90-5356-921-4 |page=380 }}</ref>  It is opposed to [[multiple citizenship]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Acquisition and Loss of Nationality: Policies and Trends in 15 European States |last=Baub\u00f6ck |first=Rainer |author2=Ersboll, Eva |year=2006 |publisher=Amsterdam University Press |location=Amsterdam |page=237 |isbn=978-90-5356-920-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nFmjkTnXNQAC }}</ref>\n\nThe party is marked out from the other parties by being [[Eurosceptic]],<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 220</ref> sharing this position with only the [[far left]],<ref name=\"Dumont 95\">Dumont et al (2006), p. 95</ref> and being the country's most [[Souverainism|sovereigntist]] party.<ref name=\"Maier 144\">Maier et al (2004), p. 144</ref>  The leadership had supported the proposed [[European Constitution]], endorsing it in the [[2004 European Parliament election in Luxembourg|2004 European election]],<ref name=\"Maier 144\" /> before changing its position in the spring of 2005 under pressure from party members.<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 92</ref>  In its criticism of the [[European Union|EU]], the party puts emphasis on the [[democratic deficit]] and [[Transparency (behavior)|transparency]].<ref name=\"Dumont 95\" />  However, in heavily [[pro-Europeanism|pro-European]] Luxembourg, the ADR had always fared worse in European elections than on national elections, which were held on the same day.<ref>Maier et al (2004), p. 143</ref> This was the case only until 2014, when the party achieved a slightly better score than it had in the early 2013 national elections, managing to beat the [[LSAP]] in the majority of communes.\n\n==Political support==\nThe ADR's primary political base are the CSV's 'traditional, rural and rightist' voters.<ref>Van Hecke et al (2004), p. 180</ref>  Although the ADR is seen to take votes from the right wing of the CSV,<ref>Van Hecke et al (2004), p. 182</ref> more ADR voters declare themselves to be [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] than either the CSV or DP.<ref>Van Hecke et al (2004), p. 187</ref>  Much of the party's support is in the north of the country,<ref name=\"Dumont 124\">Dumont et al (2006), p. 124</ref> where the ADR received its strongest support in the 1999 (16.7%), 2004 (14.7%) and [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 2009|2009 Chamber elections]] (10.3%). In 2013 however it received its highest share of the vote in the [[Est (Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg constituency)|Est]] constituency.\n\nDue to the party's original purpose of pension equality, the party's electoral base is pensioners.  However, disproportionately many people under the age of 24 also see the ADR in a positive light.<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 127\u20138</ref>  ADR is particularly popular on the [[Internet]], despite the party leadership's lack of interest in the medium, due in part to its popularity amongst young people.<ref>Dumont et al (2006), p. 156</ref>  The party is most popular amongst people earning less than \u20ac30,000,<ref name=\"Dumont 124\" /> and has attracted support from the part of the CSV's core electorate that have been left out of recent economic growth.<ref>Van Hecke et al (2004), p. 195</ref>  As with the CSV and LSAP, the ADR is supported by people with less education.<ref>Van Hecke et al (2004), p. 185</ref>\n\nThe party is backed by the third-largest general trade union in the country, the small [[Neutral Union of Luxembourg Workers]] (NGL), which has been the driving force behind the ADR.<ref name=\"Immergut 815\">Immergut et al (2007), p. 815</ref>  The ADR has also been close to the [[Luxembourg Association of Retired and Invalid People]] (LRIV), which formerly backed the [[Communist Party of Luxembourg|Communist Party]].<ref name=\"Immergut 815\" />  The party has used local celebrities, such as [[Jean-Pierre Koepp]] in [[Circonscription Nord (Luxembourg)|Nord]], to boost its appeal.<ref>Immergut et al (2007), p. 849</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|-\n! Election\n! Votes\n! %\n! Seats\n! +/\u2013\n! Position\n! Government\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 1989|1989]]\n| 225,262\n| 7.9\n| {{Composition bar|4|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| {{steady}} 0\n| {{steady}} 4th\n| {{no2|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 1994|1994]]\n| 244,045\n| 9.0\n| {{Composition bar|5|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n| {{decrease}} 5th\n| {{no2|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 1999|1999]]\n| 303,734\n| 11.3\n| {{Composition bar|7|60|hex=#00ADDC}}\n| {{increase}} 2\n| {{increase}} 4th\n| {{no2|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 2004|2004]]